#section("Section 1. Research Questions")

1. *How does large-scale structure emerge from simple local interactions in nonequilibrium systems?*
A recurring feature of complex systems is the appearance of coherent macroscopic patterns arising from many locally interacting components, even in the absence of centralized control. This phenomenon appears across physical and biological contexts, yet it remains unclear which aspects of the underlying interactions are essential for the emergence of such structure and which details are incidental.

I am interested in how researchers frame this problem in practice, particularly how simplified models are constructed and interpreted without losing the behavior of interest. At my current stage, I am still developing an understanding of how modeling choices, assumptions, and constraints shape what one ultimately observes and concludes about emergence.

2. *When does complex behavior reflect genuine emergence rather than accumulated correlations?*
Not all systems that display intricate behavior exhibit meaningful emergence. Distinguishing between collective phenomena that represent new system-level behavior and those that can be reduced to individual components remains conceptually challenging. I find this distinction compelling because it forces careful attention to definitions, interpretation, and the limits of explanatory frameworks.

I am interested in how researchers identify and test criteria for emergence, and in how different modeling perspectives influence whether behavior is interpreted as emergent or merely complex. Engaging seriously with this ambiguity, rather than resolving it too quickly, is an aspect of complexity research that particularly appeals to me.

3. *Why do some complex systems remain robust under sustained perturbations while others undergo abrupt transitions?*
Many complex systems exhibit a combination of stability and fragility, maintaining functionality across a range of conditions before experiencing sudden qualitative change. Understanding how such transitions arise, and how they relate to interaction structure and feedback, is an open question with implications across disciplines.

While I do not yet have a preferred approach to studying this problem, I am interested in how such transitions are conceptualized and investigated, especially in systems where early indicators are subtle or absent. I am motivated to invest the time required to move from qualitative observation to precise questioning in order to better understand these behaviors.

#v(0.6em)

#section("Section 2. Complexity Science Research")

What draws me to the Santa Fe Institute is its emphasis on careful thinking about difficult questions that do not belong neatly to any single discipline. Rather than prioritizing polished results, SFI values the process of understanding how assumptions, interactions, and perspectives shape the behavior of complex systems.

As a physics student, much of my training so far has focused on well-defined problems with clear solution paths. While this has been valuable, I am increasingly interested in learning how to engage with problems that are less structured and more open-ended. The UCR program offers an environment where grappling seriously with such problems is expected, and where sustained effort and intellectual persistence are valued. I am applying because I want to be challenged in that way and because I am prepared to put in the work required to grow into that mode of thinking.

#v(0.6em)

#section("Section 3. Independent and Collaborative Work")

When working independently, I tend to take a deliberate and thorough approach. I am willing to spend extended time understanding background material, revisiting basic assumptions, and refining my own understanding before moving forward. I do not view this as preliminary work to rush through, but as an essential part of engaging seriously with a problem.

In collaborative settings, I bring the same level of commitment, while placing emphasis on clarity and shared understanding. I value discussions where ideas are tested, questioned, and reshaped through interaction, even when this process is slow or uncomfortable. I am comfortable contributing consistently, listening carefully, and putting in effort beyond what is strictly required in order to move a project forward. The balance between independent focus and collaborative engagement is something I take seriously and continue to develop.

